[2]
Date: Tue 4 Feb 2014
From: Hugh Baker <drhugh@sympatico.ca> [edited]


At the beginning of the 20th century, the prevailing epidemiology was that the Mongol hoards brought the plague with them, the famine that stimulated the Mongol migration west having driven together the various grain-hungry vectors required for a pandemic of _Yersinia pestis_. This point of view was partly driven by anti-Chinese politics of the time.

Toward the end of the 20th century, there was some thought that the Romans imported the plague accidentally into the Mediterranean area by their incessant exploration of central Africa looking for ivory. The deeper into the forest the searches penetrated, the more they were exposed to the wild rodent vector of the bacillus, thus allowing the ship-board rats to acquire the fleas of the rodents of the deep forest. Due to the habit of burying at sea crew or passengers that died in transit, it took a while for human cases to manifest in Roman cities. If this scenario is true, it is probable that the Mongols took the plague BACK to the Far East, thus introducing it to a naive population.

That the Justinian strain and the Hong Kong strain are so significantly different may be an example of isolation of a population and allowing it to diverge by rapid expansion into a new niche.

--
Hugh J Baker, DVM
Etobicoke, Ontario
Canada
<drhugh@sympatico.ca>

